              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                    It was the first time that I have read a history book intently with such a painful mixture of emotions. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>    The author begins by reporting the terrifying experiences of the Arawaks of the Bahama Island  followed by the arrival of Columbus. As Las Casas says in his book, History of the Indies, &quot; so that from 1494 to 1508, over three million people had perished from war, slavery, and the mines. Who in future generations will believe this? I myself writing as a knowledgeable eyewitness can hardly believe it......&quot;<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>    The acts committed by the Spaniards led by Columbus were far foreign to human nature, and I trembled as I read about the details of the enslavement and the genocide launched against the Indians. These Indians, running to greet Columbus and his sailors, bringing them food, water and gifts with munificent hospitality, were considered by Columbus as fine tools for satisfying the frenzy for gold in the early capitalist of states in Europe. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>    The beginning the European invasion of the Indian settlements in the Americas consisted of conquest, slavery and death. However, in the history books given to children in the United States, as the author notices, such invasion starts with heroic adventure without bloodshed. So the chapter discusses more than the deception and brutality behind the massacre of Indians. The author tries to answer the question, that is, when reporting to the readers, how should the historians deal with such dishonorable facts. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>   Samuel Eliot Morison, the Harvard Historian is cited as an example. He refuses to lie about columbus or omit the story of mass murder, rather, he describes it as complete genocide. Meanwhile, he mentions the truth quickly on one page and then buries it in a mass of other information more important to him. Finally Morison judges Columbus as a seaman creating grand romance with outstanding qualities despite some faults and defects. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>    The author opposes such attitude using a convincing argument. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>    Firstly, he analyses by analogy between the cartographers and historians. Selection, simplification and emphasis are as natural and inevitable for cartographers as for historians, because the former must flatten and distort the shape of earth, then choose useful geographic information so as to produce a drawing for practical purposes. Then the author analyses two notable distinctions between such two jobs. For one thing, the mapmaker's distortion comes out of technical necessity, while the historian's distortion, which is released into a world contending interests, is ideological. For another, contrary to the obvious demonstration of the existence of distortion in the map, the ideological interest is deliberately hidden. The emphasis and deemphasis of the facts are presented as if all readers of history had common interest which historians serve to the best of their ability. The author then concluded by pointing out that, by emphasizing the heroism of Columbus as navigators and discoverers and deemphasize their genocide is an ideological choice, which serves unwittingly to justify what was done. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>    Secondly, the author stresses the importance of disclosing the hidden episodes of the past. He insists that the new possibilities which can make the history creative consist in the fugitive moments of compassion rather than the solid centuries of warfare. And to understand the complexities of history helps us to learn an instructive and valuable lesson. As far as I am concerned, the authors'  attitude help me to shed light on governments' attempts to ensnare ordinary people in a giant web of nationhood pretending to a common interest through politics and culture. Such argument reminds me of a statement, &quot;the cry of the poor is not always just, but if you don't listen to it, you will never know what justice is.&quot;<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>   Finally, holding such attitude, the author reports what Columbus did to the Arawaks of the Bahamas, Cortes dis to the Aztecs of Mexico, Pizarro to the Incas of Peru and the English settlers of Virginia and Massachusetts to the Powhatans and the Pequos. Noticeably, the aggressors almost took the same tactics, such as choosing massacre as the way to destroy the Indians' will to resist, and finding the excuse to wage wars to exterminate disobedient tribes. By making an intensive and in-depth research about these events, the author kept skeptical of excuse cited by the people, who consider the bloodshed and deceit happened in response to &quot;a real human need&quot;, which was described by Roger Williams as &quot;a depraved appetite after the great vanities, dreams and shadows of this vanishing life&quot;. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>    Was such murder of whole peoples a necessity for the human race to progress from savagery to civilization? Obviously not, the author answers. He records the later failure of Spain, pointing out European hopes that went away.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>    The most impressive part of the passage lies in the author's description of the beautiful culture developed by the Indian before the invasion. Such description covers their advanced agricultural skills, altruistic common property spirit, family and sex relationships, law development and cultural heritage retention. According to the history records, Columbus and his successors were not coming into an empty wilderness, but a place where the culture was complex, where human relations were more egalitarian than in Europe, and where the nature and the people more beautifully worked out than perhaps any place in the world.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>    I learned a lot from such a process in which the author critically made judgments about Columbus and his successors without the losses that are either unmentioned or mentioned quickly.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Dec.10, 2016<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>    
                  <div class="col-rec-con clearfix">
                    







